				|
				<a href="http://www.thesurvivalpodcast.com/calls-3-16-12/comment-page-1#comment-163585">
				March 16, 2012 at 8:00 pm</a>
					|
													</span><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
		</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->
		
		<div class="comment-body"><p>Sarah,</p>
<p>Thanks for the kind words.  One thing I should have mentioned that escaped me during my reply was that laying hens will lay past three years.  I&#8217;ve read comments from folks that say they have hens 5+ years old who are still laying.  And if they get the majority of their feed from grazing and ranging, then the economics of keeping them longer &#8220;might&#8221; work.  That being said, hens do have a set amount of eggs they can lay and the majority of those eggs come in the first three laying seasons (maybe, maybe four).  I&#8217;ve personally experienced a deep drop in egg production in year three to a point where the eggs produced didn&#8217;t justify the grain and labor involved.  But my perspective is from a pure business standpoint.  Older hens do tend to become pets, and folks often times have a hard time turning them into chicken and noodles.  But it can&#8217;t be disputed that 18 months is way to young, and the best efficiency comes in the first 24-36 months of life.</p>
<p>Thanks again to Jack for allowing me to be a part of the show!</p>
</div>

